🚀 Day 10 – Debugging Data Filtering & Boolean Indexing in Pandas
Python Debugging Lab (14-Day Series)

Today I practiced debugging one of the most important skills in data analysis:

👉 Filtering datasets using Boolean indexing in Pandas.

Filtering looks simple, but small mistakes in conditions, operators, or parentheses can cause incorrect results or runtime errors.

Learning to debug filters is essential when working with real datasets.

🔍 Topics Covered

Boolean indexing in Pandas

Combining multiple conditions

Using & instead of and

Importance of parentheses in filtering

Creating separate boolean masks for debugging

💡 Key Learning #1 – Boolean Filtering

Example:

import pandas as pd

df = pd.DataFrame({
    "price":[200,350,500],
    "rating":[4.2,4.7,4.8]
})

filtered = df[df["rating"] >= 4.5]
print(filtered)

This selects only rows where rating is at least 4.5.

💡 Key Learning #2 – Combining Multiple Conditions

Example:

filtered = df[(df["rating"] >= 4.5) & (df["price"] >= 300)]

Important rule:

Use & for combining conditions in Pandas.

Using and will cause an error.

💡 Key Learning #3 – Boolean Masks for Debugging

Instead of writing one long filter, creating masks helps debugging.

Example:

rating_mask = df["rating"] >= 4.5
price_mask = df["price"] >= 300

filtered = df[rating_mask & price_mask]

This approach makes debugging easier because each condition can be tested separately.

💡 Key Learning #4 – Parentheses Are Important

Without parentheses, filtering can break.

Correct:

(df["rating"] >= 4.5) & (df["price"] >= 300)

This ensures Python evaluates each condition properly.

🎯 Why This Matters

Boolean filtering is used everywhere in data work:

Cleaning datasets

Selecting relevant records

Preparing data for machine learning

Feature engineering

Mastering filtering logic helps avoid subtle bugs in data pipelines.

